athers. The Greek text and French translation, the first ever complete translation into a living language, are accompanied by a study that sheds new light on the text and the controversial context that underlies it. It also takes into consideration the traditions Africanus uses, one of which seems to go back to a circle claiming to be related to the family of Jesus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aEusebius von Caesarea. 4aEvangelien. 4aJesus Genealogie. 4aJulius Africanus. 4aPatristische Exegese. 7aRELIGION / Bible / Commentaries / New Testament.2bisacsh  aEusebius of Cesarea.  aGenealogy of Jesus.  aGospels.  aJulius Africanus.  aPatristic Exegesis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET THEOLOGIE/RELIGIONSWISS./JUDAISTIK  2011z9783110261271oZDB-23-DGF0 cprintz978311024099340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311024100640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110241006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110241006/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2011  aZDB-23-DGGb2011  aZDB-23-GTRc2000d2014